               <interp inst="t18420822-2556" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420822"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420822-2556" type="date" value="18420822"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420822-2556-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2556-18420822 t18420822-2556-offence-1 t18420822-2556-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2556. <persName id="def1-2556-18420822" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2556-18420822" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2556-18420822" type="surname" value="BAVIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2556-18420822" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM BAVIN</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420822-2556-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2556-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2556-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp> for feloniously assaulting <persName id="t18420822-name-1898" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1898" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1898" type="surname" value="NASH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1898" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420822-2556-offence-1 t18420822-name-1898"></join>James Nash</persName>, on the <rs id="t18420822-cd-355" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420822-2556-offence-1 t18420822-cd-355"></join>20th of August</rs>, and cutting and wounding him in and upon the head, with intent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Mr. Charnoch conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1899" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1899" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1899" type="surname" value="NASH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1899" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES NASH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chair and sofa maker, and live in Broadwall, Stamford-street, Surrey—the prisoner was my journeyman. On Satur<lb></lb>day night last, about eleven o'clock, he came to be settled with—he pro<lb></lb>duced his account to me—there was a difference between us as to the charges, which were more than I thought I should pay—he called me a b—ferret-eyed looking b—, and a shuffling trickster, said said he should like to give me something—I then sent for a policeman, who heard me tell him, what he had done I would pay him for, and when the other work was finished, I would settle for that—he then appeared more calm, and the constable left—I proceeded to settle with him—he went and sat at the end of the room, and I was settling with the other men—while I was sit<lb></lb>ting down writing, he got up, came behind me, and in an instant I felt a tremendous crash on my head, three times; had I not put my hand up, to save the second blow, I believe death must have been the consequence, for I received that blow on my hand instead of my head—I cannot say who struck the blow—I became insensible, and recollect nothing more till I found myself reviving in the surgeon's shop—I was afterwards attended by the surgeon of St. Thomas's Hospital—I managed to go out a little way on Sunday evening, but felt so faint I was obliged to return.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1900" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1900" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1900" type="surname" value="BUCHANAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1900" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BUCHANAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Mr. Nash—I was there on Saturday evening while he and the prisoner were settling some accounts—there was a dispute with the prisoner—a policeman was sent for, and he became quiet—after that he sat down in the room by himself—the pro<lb></lb>secutor began to settle with another man—I saw the prisoner get off his seat, walk round behind the prosecutor, take an empty champagne bottle off the drawers, and strike the prosecutor over the head with it as hard as he could, apparently—master had his hat off, and was sitting at the table—he struck him three times with it—he said nothing—the prosecutor got up and went out—he staggered outside the door—his head bled a good deal—the bottle was broken all to pieces—I think it broke with the se<lb></lb>cond blow, and the third was given with the neck of it—I ran to master's assistance, went over to the doctor's to him, and saw him sitting, bleeding in a chair—he was sensible then—the prisoner was quite sober—I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1901" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1901" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1901" type="surname" value="MURRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1901" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MURRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carpenter, and joiner. I live at No. 2, Black-horse-court, Farringdon-street. On Saturday evening last, I was at Mr. Wash's house, and heard a dispute about the prisoner's account—I went in with the policeman, who left—the prosecutor was sitting at the table—the prisoner took up a bottle—he pushed a man against me as I stood in the passage, to get at the bottle—he was behind Mr. Nash—he struck Mr. Nash three times across the head with it, as hard as he could—part of the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220274"></xptr>
               <p>bottle flew over me—the last blow was struck with the neck of it—Nash bled, and was taken to a doctor's—the prisoner came out of the room—I seized him, and gave him to the policeman—he was perfectly sober.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1902" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1902" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1902" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1902" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. On Saturday evening last I was called in to Nash—there were words between him and the prisoner—they were quieter, and before I had got a few yards from the house, I heard a dreadful smash, and a cry of, "Murder and police"—I went back—Nash passed me as I went to the house—the blood was running from his head—I have his clothes here—I took the prisoner into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1903" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1903" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1903" type="surname" value="FREEMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1903" type="given" value="HENRY PETTNER"></interp>HENRY PETTNER FREEMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surgeon and dresser at St. Tho<lb></lb>mas's hospital. Nash has been under my care since Tuesday—I examined his head on Tuesday—it had been dressed before I saw it—he had an in<lb></lb>cised wound, similar to one made by glass, about an inch, or rather more, long—it was only one wound—it extended nearly to the bone—it was not dangerous, but might have become so—he complained of pain in his head, but had no fever—I saw the fragments of the bottle—it appears to be a common champagne bottle—I consider that a dangerous sort of instrument.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. He refused to pay my wages; I told him that was wrong; he got up, seized hold of me, and told me to protect myself, I got hold of the bottle, and hit him twice over the head.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18420822-2556-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2556-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2556-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy by the Prosecutor</hi>
                  </rs>.—
